1
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:11,720
CLARA: Hello! Hello!

2
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:14,440
Hello, Earth.
We have a terrible decision to make.

3
00:00:14,520 --> 00:00:16,680
It is an uncertain decision

4
00:00:16,760 --> 00:00:19,360
and we don't have a lot of time.

5
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:21,480
The man who

6
00:00:21,560 --> 00:00:24,360
normally helps, he's gone.

7
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:27,240
Maybe he's not coming back.
In fact, I...

8
00:00:27,960 --> 00:00:29,960
(SIGHS) I really don't think he is.

9
00:00:31,080 --> 00:00:32,800
We're on our own.

10
00:00:33,640 --> 00:00:34,640
So...

11
00:00:38,720 --> 00:00:42,360
An innocent life versus
the future of all mankind.

12
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:45,520
We have 45 minutes to decide.

13
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:49,200
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

14
00:01:24,680 --> 00:01:26,080
Courtney Woods.

15
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:27,400
Doctor, she's gone crazy,

16
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:28,960
she's uncontrollable.

17
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,640
She took your psychic paper,
she's been using it as fake ID.

18
00:01:31,720 --> 00:01:32,720
-To get into museums?
-No, no, no,

19
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:34,680
to buy White Lightning
or alcopops or whatever.

20
00:01:34,760 --> 00:01:36,560
I've no idea what you're talking about.

21
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:38,320
-What is Courtney Woods?
-She's one of my Year 10s.

22
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:39,560
She was in the Tardis.

23
00:01:39,640 --> 00:01:41,120
-Doing what?
-Throwing up.

24
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:42,600
Oh, her. Oh, that was ages ago.

25
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:44,920
Look, she says you told her
that she wasn't special.

26
00:01:45,800 --> 00:01:46,960
Rubbish.

27
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:49,000
She says that's what
sent her off the rails.

28
00:01:49,080 --> 00:01:51,600
-(SCOFFS)
-Doctor! I know, I know!

29
00:01:51,680 --> 00:01:54,120
But you say something like that
to somebody, it hurts,

30
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:57,400
especially if you're somebody
of her age, especially if you're you.

31
00:01:57,480 --> 00:01:59,360
Doctor, it can affect her whole life.

32
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:00,680
(SCOFFS)

33
00:02:01,240 --> 00:02:02,520
Oi! Give over!

34
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:03,960
I got stuff to clean up with!

35
00:02:04,040 --> 00:02:05,640
-What?
-And I got these from the chemist.

36
00:02:05,720 --> 00:02:08,160
-Vortex Manipulators?
-Travel sickness.

37
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:11,800
Good. Because I don't like
people being sick in my Tardis.

38
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:13,480
No being sick. And no hanky-panky.

39
00:02:13,560 --> 00:02:15,880
-Doctor!
-Sorry, that's the rules.

40
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:17,600
Look, Courtney,
you're not going to be needing those

41
00:02:17,680 --> 00:02:20,240
because you're not going
to be doing any travelling.

42
00:02:20,320 --> 00:02:23,480
-Doctor, will you just, just tell her?
-Tell her what?

43
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:24,800
Tell her that she's special.

44
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:27,720
Have you gone bananas?

45
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:30,640
Do you really think I'm not special?

46
00:02:33,080 --> 00:02:35,440
You can't just take me away like that.

47
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:39,480
It's like you kicked a big hole in,
in the side of my life.

48
00:02:39,560 --> 00:02:43,040
You really think it?
I'm nothing? I'm not special?

49
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:48,040
Oh, God!

50
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:53,400
How'd you like to be
the first woman on the moon?

51
00:02:53,480 --> 00:02:55,080
Is that special enough for you?

52
00:02:56,120 --> 00:02:57,720
-Yeah, all right.
-Okay.

53
00:02:57,800 --> 00:02:59,800
Now we can do something interesting.

54
00:02:59,880 --> 00:03:02,000
Hey! Doctor!

55
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:16,640
This isn't the moon.

56
00:03:16,720 --> 00:03:19,760
-Where are we?
-On a recycled space shuttle.

57
00:03:19,840 --> 00:03:24,600
2049, judging by that prototype version
of the Bennett oscillator.

58
00:03:26,760 --> 00:03:28,640
Where's the gravity coming from?

59
00:03:35,760 --> 00:03:37,200
What are they?

60
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:42,040
-About 100 nuclear bombs.
-(ALARM BEEPING)

61
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:48,320
Ah. We're on our way to the moon.

62
00:03:52,640 --> 00:03:54,960
Check that,
we're about to crash into it!

63
00:03:55,040 --> 00:03:56,680
Hold on! Hold on!

64
00:03:57,360 --> 00:04:00,560
(GRUNTS) Why didn't you just
tell her you didn't mean it?

65
00:04:11,160 --> 00:04:12,840
Who the hell do you think you are?

66
00:04:14,080 --> 00:04:15,480
Why have you got
all these nuclear bombs?

67
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:17,800
I'm not going to give you
another chance.

68
00:04:18,240 --> 00:04:20,200
Oh, well, you're just going
to have to shoot us, then.

69
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:21,800
Shoot the little girl first.

70
00:04:21,880 --> 00:04:23,280
-What?
-Yes,

71
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:25,720
she doesn't want to stand there
and watch us getting shot, does she?

72
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:26,960
She'd be terrified.

73
00:04:27,040 --> 00:04:29,520
Girl first,
then her teacher and then me.

74
00:04:30,080 --> 00:04:32,720
You'll have to spend a lot of time
shooting me

75
00:04:32,800 --> 00:04:35,520
because I will keep on regenerating.

76
00:04:36,240 --> 00:04:37,360
In fact, I'm not entirely sure

77
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:40,520
that I won't keep on
regenerating forever.

78
00:04:40,600 --> 00:04:43,120
-Doctor, what are you doing?
-Gravity test.

79
00:04:43,880 --> 00:04:46,760
So it'll be very
time-consuming and messy

80
00:04:46,840 --> 00:04:49,080
and rather wasteful

81
00:04:49,160 --> 00:04:52,040
because I think I might just
possibly be able to help you.

82
00:04:52,120 --> 00:04:55,120
You see,
I am a super-intelligent alien being

83
00:04:55,200 --> 00:04:57,360
who flies in time and space.

84
00:04:57,440 --> 00:04:58,720
Are you going to shoot me?

85
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:01,960
-No.
-Good.

86
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:04,840
Why have you got
all these nuclear bombs?

87
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:07,360
No, no, no. Easier question,

88
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:09,520
what's wrong with my yo-yo?

89
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:12,600
Doctor, it goes up and down.

90
00:05:12,680 --> 00:05:13,840
Bingo!

91
00:05:15,880 --> 00:05:17,400
-Ah.
-A-ha!

92
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:22,240
We should all be bouncing about
this cabin like fluffy little clouds.

93
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:24,080
But we're not.

94
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,200
What is the matter with the moon?

95
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:31,600
Nobody knows.

96
00:05:32,320 --> 00:05:34,960
Do you know what's wrong with the moon?

97
00:05:35,040 --> 00:05:37,880
-It's put on weight.
-How can the moon put on weight?

98
00:05:37,960 --> 00:05:39,240
Well, lots of ways.

99
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:43,520
Gravity bombs, axis alignment systems,
planet shellers.

100
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:44,880
So, it's alien?

101
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:47,320
Must be causing chaos on Earth.

102
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:51,520
The tides will be so high
that they will drown whole cities!

103
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:54,000
-Yeah.
-So what are you doing about it?

104
00:05:59,920 --> 00:06:01,120
This?

105
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:03,960
That's what you do with aliens,
isn't it? Blow them up?

106
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:12,840
COURTNEY: Wow!

107
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:14,560
Wow!

108
00:06:20,080 --> 00:06:22,400
One small thing for a thing,

109
00:06:22,480 --> 00:06:25,080
one enormous thing for a thingy-thing!

110
00:06:25,160 --> 00:06:27,160
Well, so much for history.

111
00:06:51,720 --> 00:06:54,840
LUNDVIK: There was a mining survey.
Mexicans.

112
00:06:54,920 --> 00:06:57,320
Something happened up here,
nobody knows what.

113
00:06:57,400 --> 00:06:59,840
That's when the trouble began
back on Earth.

114
00:06:59,920 --> 00:07:02,120
High tide everywhere at once.

115
00:07:02,200 --> 00:07:04,960
The greatest natural disaster
in history.

116
00:07:08,440 --> 00:07:09,680
Cobwebs?

117
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:12,880
Henry, go back and prime the bombs.

118
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:16,680
-Um, is there any instructions?
-(SIGHS)

119
00:07:17,240 --> 00:07:19,640
There's a switch on each of them.
The light goes red.

120
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:21,320
And it won't go off?

121
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:23,600
No, not till I've fiddled
with this thing.

122
00:07:24,160 --> 00:07:25,280
Okay.

123
00:07:28,400 --> 00:07:29,680
Shall we?

124
00:07:30,560 --> 00:07:32,880
DOCTOR: Is that the best you could get?

125
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:36,160
LUNDVIK: Second-hand space shuttle,
third-hand astronauts.

126
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:08,480
DOCTOR: How many people here?
LUNDVIK: Four.

127
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:10,720
Minera Luna San Pedro.

128
00:08:10,800 --> 00:08:12,240
It was privately financed.

129
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:13,960
They were doing
a mineral survey up here.

130
00:08:14,640 --> 00:08:17,840
Messages? Mayday? SOS?

131
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:20,600
Pretty much all the satellites
had been whacked out of orbit.

132
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:24,240
They managed to send back some screams.

133
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:27,680
So, then you came up
to rescue them with your bombs?

134
00:08:27,920 --> 00:08:29,240
Not quite.

135
00:08:29,720 --> 00:08:32,240
-They disappeared 10 years ago.
-Nobody came?

136
00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:34,600
-There was no shuttle.
-You had one.

137
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:35,960
It was in a museum.

138
00:08:36,440 --> 00:08:38,400
They'd cut the back off it
so kids could ride in it.

139
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:43,000
We'd stopped going into space.
Nobody cared.

140
00:08:43,080 --> 00:08:44,480
-Not until...
-(COURTNEY SCREAMS)

141
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:46,280
-Courtney!
-(COURTNEY WHIMPERING)

142
00:08:48,200 --> 00:08:49,600
CLARA: Oh, my God.

143
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:52,360
Doctor, tell me there wasn't
anyone inside that thing.

144
00:08:52,440 --> 00:08:54,720
I could, but it wouldn't make it true.

145
00:08:55,160 --> 00:08:57,320
I'll get some power back on.

146
00:08:58,800 --> 00:09:00,320
CLARA: Come on.

147
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:09,640
Courtney, come here. Don't look.

148
00:09:16,520 --> 00:09:18,160
-You all right?
-I'm okay.

149
00:09:18,240 --> 00:09:21,400
Hey, look. Look at me. Look!

150
00:09:21,480 --> 00:09:23,520
It's all right if you're not.

151
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:24,880
I'm fine.

152
00:09:29,440 --> 00:09:30,440
What did it?

153
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:33,200
DOCTOR: Maybe something

154
00:09:33,280 --> 00:09:36,560
trying to find out
how you were put together.

155
00:09:37,560 --> 00:09:39,920
Or maybe how you tasted.

156
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:43,920
Do we have guns?

157
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:46,240
Not unless you brought some.

158
00:09:49,400 --> 00:09:50,840
Chicken, apparently.

159
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:52,680
(LOW WHIRRING)

160
00:09:54,360 --> 00:09:55,800
Save the air.

161
00:09:56,720 --> 00:09:57,920
(EXHALES)

162
00:10:09,960 --> 00:10:11,680
(MACHINE BEEPS)

163
00:10:17,880 --> 00:10:19,680
They didn't find anything.

164
00:10:19,760 --> 00:10:21,440
-Eh?
-The Mexicans.

165
00:10:22,680 --> 00:10:25,080
They didn't find any minerals
on the moon at all.

166
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:26,880
Nada.

167
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:38,240
Oh.

168
00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:41,120
-Oh?
-Lines of tectonic stress.

169
00:10:41,200 --> 00:10:42,440
That's the Mare Fecunditatis.

170
00:10:42,520 --> 00:10:44,760
It's been there since
the Apollo days, it's always been there.

171
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:47,040
No, no, no. These are much, much bigger.

172
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:49,920
Sea of Tranquillity.

173
00:10:50,760 --> 00:10:51,960
Sea of Nectar.

174
00:10:52,840 --> 00:10:54,480
Sea of Ingenuity.

175
00:10:55,360 --> 00:10:56,840
Sea of Crises.

176
00:10:58,080 --> 00:10:59,320
Meaning?

177
00:11:00,760 --> 00:11:03,840
Meaning, Clara, that the moon,

178
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:06,120
this little planetoid
that's been tagging along beside you

179
00:11:06,200 --> 00:11:07,960
for 100 million years,

180
00:11:08,040 --> 00:11:12,040
which gives you light at night
and seas to sail on,

181
00:11:12,120 --> 00:11:13,800
is in the process of falling to bits.

182
00:11:14,120 --> 00:11:15,760
(RUMBLING)

183
00:11:16,960 --> 00:11:18,560
(PANTING)

184
00:11:29,120 --> 00:11:31,160
Hello, Captain? Captain?

185
00:11:31,720 --> 00:11:34,000
-(SCUTTLING)
-Captain? Oh!

186
00:11:42,960 --> 00:11:44,920
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

187
00:11:49,560 --> 00:11:51,720
-(SCREECHING)
-(SCREAMING)

188
00:12:00,640 --> 00:12:02,840
(LOUD SCREECHING IN DISTANCE)

189
00:12:03,880 --> 00:12:06,280
-What the hell was that?
-Duke, is that you?

190
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:09,280
DUKE: (OVER RADIO)
I don't sound anything like that.

191
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:11,360
Can you try and get the lights back on?

192
00:12:11,440 --> 00:12:12,720
That's what I am doing.

193
00:12:14,080 --> 00:12:16,440
Torch, give me your torch.
Whatever it is, it's in here.

194
00:12:23,040 --> 00:12:24,800
(SCUTTLING)

195
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:28,280
-(SCREECHING IN DISTANCE)
-(GASPS)

196
00:12:46,320 --> 00:12:47,360
I think we've found your alien.

197
00:12:49,080 --> 00:12:50,960
Back, back, back! We need a door.

198
00:12:51,040 --> 00:12:52,880
-A door, a door!
-Here! Here!

199
00:12:54,360 --> 00:12:56,360
-The door's locked.
-Come on, come on!

200
00:12:56,440 --> 00:12:58,920
-DOCTOR: There's no power to work it.
-Courtney!

201
00:13:00,320 --> 00:13:01,920
-DOCTOR: Come on!
-Doctor...

202
00:13:03,480 --> 00:13:05,160
DOCTOR: Stay still.
It's sensing movement.

203
00:13:05,240 --> 00:13:07,560
It can't see you. Fast movement.

204
00:13:08,160 --> 00:13:10,920
There must be another exit
through there.

205
00:13:12,680 --> 00:13:13,880
Slowly.

206
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:17,200
-(SCUTTLING)
-Slowly.

207
00:13:21,120 --> 00:13:23,240
(WHISPERING) Head to that exit.

208
00:13:23,320 --> 00:13:25,400
-DOCTOR: Slowly, slowly.
-Take my hand.

209
00:13:26,560 --> 00:13:28,080
Slowly. Slowly.

210
00:13:29,840 --> 00:13:31,360
Gently, gently.

211
00:13:34,560 --> 00:13:36,800
When I say run, run.

212
00:13:36,880 --> 00:13:38,720
Who made you the boss?

213
00:13:39,440 --> 00:13:40,560
Well, you say run, then!

214
00:13:41,720 --> 00:13:42,720
Duke!

215
00:13:43,440 --> 00:13:45,000
-(SCREECHING)
-(SCREAMING)

216
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:46,080
Duke!

217
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:50,360
Run! We have power. Run!

218
00:13:51,720 --> 00:13:54,160
-Quick! It's shutting!
-Miss!

219
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:56,760
Courtney! Courtney!

220
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:58,120
-Miss!
-Courtney!

221
00:13:58,200 --> 00:13:59,440
(DUKE SCREAMING)

222
00:13:59,520 --> 00:14:00,560
The power's gone again.

223
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:02,520
It's killed him. It's coming in here!

224
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:04,920
Doctor, it's coming in here!

225
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:06,840
-You'll be okay!
-Henry? Henry?

226
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,360
Courtney, look at me. Look at me!
Courtney! Try and get to the wall!

227
00:14:11,680 --> 00:14:14,560
Try and get yourself down here.

228
00:14:16,360 --> 00:14:17,800
Courtney, grab my yo-yo!

229
00:14:21,240 --> 00:14:22,240
(GRUNTS)

230
00:14:25,640 --> 00:14:27,160
- (HISSING)
-(SCREAMING)

231
00:14:28,080 --> 00:14:29,080
DOCTOR: Courtney!

232
00:14:29,880 --> 00:14:31,840
(CREATURE SCREECHING)

233
00:14:34,840 --> 00:14:35,880
Courtney.

234
00:14:35,960 --> 00:14:38,800
Kills 99% of all known germs.

235
00:14:38,880 --> 00:14:41,560
Good stuff, Courtney.
Just don't try that at home, okay?

236
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:43,480
You all right?

237
00:14:43,840 --> 00:14:46,680
Why did I just fly? This is nuts.

238
00:14:47,760 --> 00:14:48,760
Did you say germs?

239
00:14:49,800 --> 00:14:51,920
Oh, God, this is incredible.

240
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,160
Look at the size of it,
it's the size of a badger!

241
00:14:54,240 --> 00:14:55,840
Doctor...

242
00:14:55,920 --> 00:14:58,240
It's a prokaryotic,
unicellular life form

243
00:14:58,320 --> 00:14:59,920
with non-chromosomal DNA.

244
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,280
Which, as you and me know...

245
00:15:01,360 --> 00:15:03,040
Well, not you and me,
well, you certainly not.

246
00:15:03,120 --> 00:15:06,400
As, you and me,
yes, scientists know this is a germ.

247
00:15:07,320 --> 00:15:11,000
You flew because that 1.3 billion
tonnes shifted. It moved!

248
00:15:11,680 --> 00:15:13,280
It's an unstable mass.

249
00:15:13,880 --> 00:15:16,560
-I'm scared, miss.
-Okay.

250
00:15:17,080 --> 00:15:19,120
He'd just had a granddaughter.

251
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:21,720
Elina. She was his first.

252
00:15:22,800 --> 00:15:25,640
He was my teacher.
He taught me how to fly.

253
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:28,080
We were both given the sack
on the same day.

254
00:15:28,160 --> 00:15:31,160
Which way to the Mare Fecunditatis?

255
00:15:31,240 --> 00:15:33,240
Please can I go home now?

256
00:15:34,680 --> 00:15:36,120
I'm really...

257
00:15:37,320 --> 00:15:39,720
I'm really sorry

258
00:15:40,120 --> 00:15:42,080
but I'd like to go home.

259
00:15:45,160 --> 00:15:46,440
LUNDVIK: Henry, come in.

260
00:15:46,520 --> 00:15:49,320
If you don't mind, Henry, come in.

261
00:15:49,400 --> 00:15:52,880
CLARA: Doctor, this is dangerous now.

262
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:54,240
DOCTOR: It was dangerous before.

263
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:55,560
Everything's dangerous
if you want it to be.

264
00:15:55,640 --> 00:15:57,480
Eating chips is dangerous.
Crossing the road.

265
00:15:57,560 --> 00:15:59,400
It's no way to live your life.

266
00:15:59,840 --> 00:16:01,520
Tell her, you're supposed
to be teaching her!

267
00:16:01,600 --> 00:16:04,240
Look, I have a duty of care, okay?
You know what that is?

268
00:16:04,320 --> 00:16:07,760
Of course I know what a duty
of care is. What are you suggesting?

269
00:16:07,840 --> 00:16:11,000
-She's fine. What are you, 357
-Fifteen!

270
00:16:15,880 --> 00:16:18,200
-Don't touch anything.
-You got any games?

271
00:16:18,280 --> 00:16:20,200
Oh, don't be so stupid!

272
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:23,320
-Can I get reception up here?
-Get in.

273
00:16:26,120 --> 00:16:29,000
Why are you shutting her in?
We don't need to stay, do we?

274
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:30,480
-Eh?
-It's obvious, isn't it?

275
00:16:30,560 --> 00:16:32,640
-The moon doesn't break up.
-How do you know?

276
00:16:33,680 --> 00:16:37,760
Well, because I've been in the future
and the moon is still there.

277
00:16:37,960 --> 00:16:38,960
I think.

278
00:16:41,480 --> 00:16:43,280
You know the moon is still there, right?

279
00:16:43,360 --> 00:16:44,760
Maybe it isn't the moon.

280
00:16:44,840 --> 00:16:48,400
Maybe it's a hologram or a big
painting or a special effect.

281
00:16:48,480 --> 00:16:50,080
Maybe it's a completely different moon.

282
00:16:50,160 --> 00:16:53,040
-But you would know.
-I would?

283
00:16:53,120 --> 00:16:55,720
If the moon fell to bits in 2049,
somebody would've mentioned it,

284
00:16:55,800 --> 00:16:57,520
it would have come up in conversation.

285
00:16:57,600 --> 00:17:00,000
So it doesn't break up,
so the world doesn't end.

286
00:17:00,080 --> 00:17:02,440
So let's just get in the Tardis and go!

287
00:17:02,520 --> 00:17:05,320
Clara, there are some moments
in time that I simply can't see.

288
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:11,440
Little eye-blinks.

289
00:17:11,800 --> 00:17:14,240
They don't look the same
as other things.

290
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:15,800
They're not clear,

291
00:17:15,880 --> 00:17:17,200
they're fuzzy,

292
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:18,720
they're grey.

293
00:17:19,520 --> 00:17:22,600
Little moments
in which big things are decided.

294
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:25,240
And this is one of them.

295
00:17:26,560 --> 00:17:28,440
Just now, I can't tell
what happens to the moon

296
00:17:28,520 --> 00:17:30,360
because whatever happens to the moon

297
00:17:31,120 --> 00:17:33,080
hasn't been decided yet.

298
00:17:33,880 --> 00:17:36,960
And it's going to be decided
here and now.

299
00:17:39,040 --> 00:17:42,480
Which very much sounds
as though it's up to us.

300
00:17:43,520 --> 00:17:45,280
Neither of you are going anywhere.

301
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:48,000
I've lost my crew.

302
00:17:48,080 --> 00:17:49,600
We were the last astronauts,

303
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:53,160
this is the last shuttle,
these are the last nuclear bombs.

304
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:56,720
We're the last chance for Earth
and you're staying to help me.

305
00:17:58,640 --> 00:17:59,760
Decision made.

306
00:18:05,480 --> 00:18:06,600
Yeah.

307
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,960
DOCTOR: What is killing the moon?

308
00:18:36,160 --> 00:18:38,000
CLARA: How can the moon die, though?

309
00:18:38,440 --> 00:18:40,840
Everything does, sooner or later.

310
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:43,200
Can we save it?

311
00:18:43,760 --> 00:18:45,800
Depends what's killing it.

312
00:18:49,320 --> 00:18:51,800
LUNDVIK: There are the other three.

313
00:19:02,880 --> 00:19:04,720
Is it those germ things, then?

314
00:19:04,800 --> 00:19:07,040
Are they like cockroaches? Is it...

315
00:19:07,120 --> 00:19:09,360
-Is it an infestation?
-Is it?

316
00:19:10,600 --> 00:19:12,400
Well, I've only seen one of them.

317
00:19:12,480 --> 00:19:14,600
It would take an awful lot more
to cause the moon

318
00:19:14,680 --> 00:19:17,520
to put on 1.3 billion tonnes.

319
00:19:20,320 --> 00:19:22,160
-Doctor!
-(SCREECHING)

320
00:19:22,240 --> 00:19:23,520
No, it's a vacuum, it won't work.

321
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:25,600
(DOCTOR GROANING)

322
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:30,640
That makes two.

323
00:19:32,680 --> 00:19:33,960
Sunlight.

324
00:19:34,040 --> 00:19:35,280
-Sunlight?
-If they're germs.

325
00:19:35,360 --> 00:19:37,280
My nan says it's the best
disinfectant there is.

326
00:19:37,360 --> 00:19:38,480
Shine your light down there.

327
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:46,960
Where have they come from?

328
00:19:47,040 --> 00:19:49,600
Maybe they've been there all the time.

329
00:19:49,680 --> 00:19:52,120
It's warmish. They're multiplying.

330
00:19:52,800 --> 00:19:55,480
Feeding. Evolving.

331
00:19:56,680 --> 00:20:00,920
Doctor, if the moon breaks up,
it'll kill us all in about 45 minutes.

332
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:03,880
I agree.
Unless something else is going on.

333
00:20:08,560 --> 00:20:09,960
There's no water on the moon.

334
00:20:10,040 --> 00:20:13,040
It's not water. It's amniotic fluid.

335
00:20:13,720 --> 00:20:15,240
The stuff that life comes from.

336
00:20:15,320 --> 00:20:17,720
-I've got to go down there.
-Doctor!

337
00:20:17,800 --> 00:20:19,360
Back to your shuttle.
Get your bombs ready.

338
00:20:19,440 --> 00:20:22,600
You, get to the Tardis.
Get safe. Get Courtney safe.

339
00:20:22,680 --> 00:20:25,240
-I will be back.
-What? No. Doctor. Doctor!

340
00:20:27,880 --> 00:20:29,080
Doctor!

341
00:20:31,920 --> 00:20:34,560
-LUNDVIK: Will he?
-(SIGHS)

342
00:20:35,120 --> 00:20:36,200
Will he be back?

343
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:41,160
If he says so, I suppose he will.

344
00:20:46,880 --> 00:20:49,200
Miss? Come in.

345
00:20:49,640 --> 00:20:50,640
Courtney?

346
00:20:50,720 --> 00:20:52,600
I'm bored. When are you coming back?

347
00:20:52,680 --> 00:20:54,400
We're on our way. What you doing?

348
00:20:54,800 --> 00:20:56,400
Putting some pictures on Tumblr.

349
00:20:56,800 --> 00:20:59,880
No! Courtney, don't put
any photos on Tumblr.

350
00:20:59,960 --> 00:21:02,280
(CHUCKLING)
My granny used to put things on Tumblr!

351
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:04,320
-(LOUD RUMBLING)
-(BOTH GASP)

352
00:21:12,600 --> 00:21:14,000
There he is.

353
00:21:27,160 --> 00:21:30,800
CLARA: Is that where we landed?
It looks so different.

354
00:21:33,600 --> 00:21:35,040
It's going down.

355
00:21:35,120 --> 00:21:36,680
CLARA: Courtney!

356
00:21:38,280 --> 00:21:40,680
-Doctor!
-We're going to have to take cover.

357
00:21:40,760 --> 00:21:42,880
-We're running out of oxygen.
-Doctor!

358
00:21:44,960 --> 00:21:47,240
Today's the day, humankind!

359
00:21:50,360 --> 00:21:51,480
Where's the Tardis?

360
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:53,120
She's in the shuttle, isn't she?
She'll turn up.

361
00:21:53,200 --> 00:21:55,560
Last time you said that, she turned
up on the wrong side of the planet!

362
00:21:55,640 --> 00:21:57,440
You two have never gotten on, have you?

363
00:21:57,520 --> 00:21:59,360
Look, we need to know where Courtney is!

364
00:21:59,440 --> 00:22:00,440
Courtney is safe.

365
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:04,120
Oh, well, do you have her phone number?

366
00:22:04,200 --> 00:22:05,560
No, no, no. Of course I don't
have her phone number!

367
00:22:05,640 --> 00:22:07,320
What about the school,
does the secretary have her number?

368
00:22:07,400 --> 00:22:09,000
(SIGHS) I can't. The secretary hates me.

369
00:22:09,080 --> 00:22:11,560
She thinks I gave her a packet
Tena Lady for Secret Santa.

370
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:14,280
Look, Courtney's posting stuff on
Tumblr. Doesn't that know where you are?

371
00:22:14,360 --> 00:22:15,840
I don't know. I'm not a historian.

372
00:22:15,920 --> 00:22:18,360
Phone. I know what the problem is.

373
00:22:19,120 --> 00:22:21,640
Oh, she can't post that!
She can't put pictures of me online!

374
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:23,520
(DEVICE WHIRRING)

375
00:22:24,800 --> 00:22:26,680
-Yeah?
-You can't put pictures of me online!

376
00:22:26,760 --> 00:22:29,280
-Are you okay?
-Uh, I'm fine. What's up?

377
00:22:29,360 --> 00:22:31,320
-You said you know what the problem is.
-Yes. Yes!

378
00:22:31,400 --> 00:22:32,960
It's a rather big problem.

379
00:22:33,040 --> 00:22:34,640
Okay. Do you want to share it
with the class?

380
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:37,120
Well, I had a little hypothesis.

381
00:22:37,200 --> 00:22:40,120
The seismic activity,
the surface breaking up,

382
00:22:40,200 --> 00:22:42,920
the variable mass,
the increase in gravity,

383
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:44,360
the fluid...

384
00:22:44,440 --> 00:22:46,360
I scanned what's down there.

385
00:22:46,440 --> 00:22:48,480
(DEVICE HUMMING)

386
00:22:49,960 --> 00:22:51,800
The moon isn't breaking apart.

387
00:22:51,880 --> 00:22:53,960
Well, actually, it is breaking
apart and rather quickly,

388
00:22:54,040 --> 00:22:56,960
we've got about an hour and a half,
but that isn't the problem.

389
00:22:57,040 --> 00:22:58,040
It's not infested.

390
00:22:58,640 --> 00:23:00,640
What are they, then, those things?

391
00:23:01,880 --> 00:23:02,880
Bacteria.

392
00:23:04,200 --> 00:23:05,760
Tiny, tiny bacteria.

393
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:08,800
Living on something very, very big.

394
00:23:09,560 --> 00:23:13,280
Something that weighs
about 1.3 billion tonnes.

395
00:23:13,360 --> 00:23:15,800
Something that's living.
Something growing.

396
00:23:16,720 --> 00:23:17,720
Growing?

397
00:23:21,560 --> 00:23:22,680
That.

398
00:23:28,160 --> 00:23:29,960
-That lives under the moon?
-No.

399
00:23:30,720 --> 00:23:31,840
What?

400
00:23:32,560 --> 00:23:34,400
That doesn't live under the moon.

401
00:23:34,480 --> 00:23:36,120
That is the moon.

402
00:23:36,560 --> 00:23:38,680
What the hell are you talking about?

403
00:23:38,880 --> 00:23:41,680
The moon isn't breaking apart.
The moon is hatching!

404
00:23:41,760 --> 00:23:42,760
Huh?

405
00:23:44,280 --> 00:23:45,960
The moon's an egg.

406
00:23:53,080 --> 00:23:54,080
Has it, um...

407
00:23:56,200 --> 00:23:59,320
-Has it always been an egg?
-Yes.

408
00:23:59,400 --> 00:24:00,760
For 100 million years or so.

409
00:24:00,840 --> 00:24:04,040
Just, just growing,
just getting ready to be born.

410
00:24:04,560 --> 00:24:07,960
Okay, so the moon
has never been the moon?

411
00:24:08,040 --> 00:24:10,040
No, no, no, no. It's never been dead.

412
00:24:10,120 --> 00:24:11,720
It's just taking a long time
to come alive.

413
00:24:12,400 --> 00:24:14,320
Is it a chicken?

414
00:24:14,400 --> 00:24:16,280
-No!
-'Cause, for a chicken

415
00:24:16,360 --> 00:24:19,640
-to have laid an egg...
-Courtney, don't spoil the moment.

416
00:24:20,720 --> 00:24:21,720
Doctor, what is it?

417
00:24:22,840 --> 00:24:24,840
I think that it's unique.

418
00:24:25,840 --> 00:24:29,520
I think that's the only one
of its kind in the universe.

419
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:31,680
I think that that is

420
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:35,480
utterly beautiful.

421
00:24:37,920 --> 00:24:39,080
How do we kill it?

422
00:24:48,320 --> 00:24:51,280
-Why do you want to kill it?
-It's a little baby.

423
00:24:52,320 --> 00:24:53,800
Doctor, how do we kill it?

424
00:24:54,400 --> 00:24:55,720
Kill the moon?

425
00:25:01,680 --> 00:25:03,160
Kill the moon.

426
00:25:03,840 --> 00:25:08,120
Well, you have about 100 of
the best man-made nuclear weapons,

427
00:25:08,200 --> 00:25:09,640
if they still work,
if that's what you want to do.

428
00:25:09,720 --> 00:25:12,160
-Doctor, wait...
-Will that do it?

429
00:25:12,240 --> 00:25:14,880
A hundred nuclear bombs set off
right where they are,

430
00:25:14,960 --> 00:25:18,000
right on top of a living,
vulnerable creature.

431
00:25:18,080 --> 00:25:20,000
It'll never feel the sun on its back.

432
00:25:20,080 --> 00:25:22,400
And then what?
Will the moon still break up?

433
00:25:22,480 --> 00:25:24,400
You said...
You said we had an hour and a half?

434
00:25:24,480 --> 00:25:26,520
Well, there'll be nothing
to make it break up.

435
00:25:26,600 --> 00:25:29,120
There'll be nothing
trying to force its way out.

436
00:25:29,200 --> 00:25:30,480
The gravity of the little dead baby

437
00:25:30,560 --> 00:25:32,120
will pull all the pieces
back together again.

438
00:25:32,200 --> 00:25:33,680
Of course, it won't be very pretty.

439
00:25:33,760 --> 00:25:36,960
You'd have an enormous corpse
floating in the sky.

440
00:25:37,800 --> 00:25:40,240
You might have some very difficult
conversations to have with your kids.

441
00:25:40,320 --> 00:25:42,200
-I don't have any kids.
-Stop.

442
00:25:42,280 --> 00:25:44,240
Right, listen, this is a,
this is a life.

443
00:25:44,320 --> 00:25:46,240
I mean, this must be
the biggest life in the universe.

444
00:25:46,640 --> 00:25:48,000
It's not even been born!

445
00:25:48,240 --> 00:25:52,200
It is killing people.
It is destroying the Earth!

446
00:25:52,280 --> 00:25:53,880
You cannot blame a baby for kicking.

447
00:25:54,400 --> 00:25:56,800
Let me tell you something.

448
00:25:56,880 --> 00:25:59,720
You want to know
what I took back from being in space?

449
00:26:00,520 --> 00:26:02,320
Look at the edge of the Earth,

450
00:26:02,400 --> 00:26:05,480
the atmosphere, that is paper-thin.

451
00:26:05,560 --> 00:26:08,480
That is the only thing
that saves us all from death,

452
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:10,680
everything else,
the stars, the blackness,

453
00:26:11,320 --> 00:26:13,440
that's all dead.

454
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:15,680
Sadly, that

455
00:26:16,360 --> 00:26:18,680
is the only life
any of us will ever know.

456
00:26:19,040 --> 00:26:20,800
There's life here.

457
00:26:21,520 --> 00:26:22,920
There's life just next door.

458
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:24,720
Look, when you've grown up a bit,
you'll realise

459
00:26:24,800 --> 00:26:26,640
that everything doesn't have to be nice.

460
00:26:26,720 --> 00:26:28,240
Some things are just bad.

461
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:30,600
Anyway, you ran away.
It's none of your business.

462
00:26:31,880 --> 00:26:33,120
COURTNEY: Doctor, I want to come back.

463
00:26:33,200 --> 00:26:34,800
Courtney, you'll be safer where you are.

464
00:26:34,880 --> 00:26:38,480
Doctor, I'm sorry. I want
to come back, okay? I want to help.

465
00:26:38,560 --> 00:26:40,400
DOCTOR: There are some DVDs
on the blue bookshelf.

466
00:26:40,480 --> 00:26:43,880
Just stick one into the Tardis console,
that'll bring you to me.

467
00:26:43,960 --> 00:26:46,040
-Right.
-Make sure you hang on to the console,

468
00:26:46,120 --> 00:26:48,120
otherwise the Tardis
will leave you behind.

469
00:26:48,200 --> 00:26:51,400
So. What do we do?

470
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:54,400
Doctor? Huh?

471
00:26:55,880 --> 00:26:57,120
Doctor, what do we do?

472
00:26:58,640 --> 00:26:59,640
Nothing.

473
00:27:00,880 --> 00:27:03,360
-What?
-We don't do anything.

474
00:27:04,400 --> 00:27:06,800
I'm sorry, Clara. I can't help you.

475
00:27:06,880 --> 00:27:08,480
Of course you can help.

476
00:27:08,560 --> 00:27:11,320
The Earth isn't my home.
The moon's not my moon. Sorry.

477
00:27:12,320 --> 00:27:14,240
Come on! Hey.

478
00:27:15,080 --> 00:27:18,680
Listen, there are moments
in every civilisation's history

479
00:27:18,760 --> 00:27:22,600
in which the whole path
of that civilisation is decided.

480
00:27:23,640 --> 00:27:24,880
The whole future path.

481
00:27:25,520 --> 00:27:28,200
Whatever future humanity might have

482
00:27:28,280 --> 00:27:32,280
depends upon the choice that is made
right here and right now.

483
00:27:34,520 --> 00:27:37,920
Now, you've got the tools to kill it.
You made them.

484
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:41,800
You brought them up here
all on your own with your own ingenuity,

485
00:27:41,880 --> 00:27:43,960
you don't need a Time Lord.

486
00:27:44,920 --> 00:27:47,320
Kill it. Or let it live.
I can't make this decision for you!

487
00:27:47,400 --> 00:27:51,200
-Yeah, well, I can't make it.
-Well, there's two of you here.

488
00:27:51,280 --> 00:27:53,840
Yeah, a schoolteacher and an astronaut.

489
00:27:53,920 --> 00:27:54,960
Who's better qualified?

490
00:27:55,040 --> 00:27:57,000
I don't know! The President of America!

491
00:27:57,080 --> 00:28:00,080
Oh, take something off his plate.
He makes far too many decisions anyway.

492
00:28:00,160 --> 00:28:03,040
-She.
-She. Sorry.

493
00:28:03,120 --> 00:28:05,560
She hasn't even been into space,
she hasn't even been to another planet.

494
00:28:05,640 --> 00:28:08,560
-How would she even know what to do?
-I am asking you for help.

495
00:28:08,640 --> 00:28:13,080
Listen, we went to dinner
in Berlin in 1937, right?

496
00:28:13,800 --> 00:28:16,880
We didn't nip out
after pudding and kill Hitler.

497
00:28:16,960 --> 00:28:18,400
I've never killed Hitler.

498
00:28:18,880 --> 00:28:21,920
And you wouldn't expect me
to kill Hitler.

499
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:25,360
The future is no more malleable
than the past.

500
00:28:25,440 --> 00:28:27,560
Okay, don't you do this
to make some kind of point.

501
00:28:27,640 --> 00:28:29,600
Sorry. Well, actually,
no, I'm not sorry.

502
00:28:29,680 --> 00:28:32,800
It's time to take
the stabilisers off your bike!

503
00:28:34,480 --> 00:28:37,320
It's your moon, womankind.

504
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:39,400
It's your choice.

505
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:44,320
-And you're just going to stand there?
-Absolutely not.

506
00:28:45,840 --> 00:28:46,840
(WHOOSHING)

507
00:28:51,200 --> 00:28:52,240
Doctor?

508
00:28:52,320 --> 00:28:54,320
A teenager, an astronaut
and a schoolteacher.

509
00:28:54,960 --> 00:28:57,520
Hang on a minute,
we can get in there, can't we?

510
00:28:57,600 --> 00:29:00,160
-You can sort it out with that thing.
-No.

511
00:29:00,240 --> 00:29:03,360
Some decisions are too important
not to make on your own.

512
00:29:03,840 --> 00:29:04,840
Doctor.

513
00:29:05,880 --> 00:29:07,080
Doctor.

514
00:29:08,280 --> 00:29:09,320
Doctor!

515
00:29:11,120 --> 00:29:12,920
(WHOOSHING)

516
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:14,600
Oh, what a prat.

517
00:29:15,600 --> 00:29:17,080
(THUDDING)

518
00:29:18,840 --> 00:29:21,080
(SCREECHING)

519
00:29:25,880 --> 00:29:27,480
I'm going to detonate the bombs, agreed?

520
00:29:28,480 --> 00:29:29,480
Agreed?

521
00:29:30,280 --> 00:29:31,280
(CRASHING)

522
00:29:33,360 --> 00:29:35,120
Hang on tight, there's been a breach!

523
00:29:45,760 --> 00:29:47,880
If we let it live, what would happen
if the moon wasn't there?

524
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:49,880
-We haven't got time for this!
-We're discussing it!

525
00:29:49,960 --> 00:29:51,760
What would happen
if the moon wasn't there?

526
00:29:51,840 --> 00:29:54,720
I have a physics book in my bag.
There's this thing on gravity.

527
00:29:54,800 --> 00:29:56,560
Super. Is there a word search?

528
00:29:56,640 --> 00:29:59,000
(SIGHS) Okay. There would be no tides.

529
00:29:59,080 --> 00:30:00,520
But we'd survive that, right?
There's, uh...

530
00:30:00,600 --> 00:30:03,720
They've knocked out the satellites.
There's no internet, no mobiles.

531
00:30:03,800 --> 00:30:04,960
I'd be fine with that.

532
00:30:05,040 --> 00:30:07,160
It's not going to just stop being there.

533
00:30:07,240 --> 00:30:09,080
Because inside the moon, miss,

534
00:30:09,160 --> 00:30:11,400
is a gigantic creature
forcing its way out.

535
00:30:11,480 --> 00:30:13,360
And when it does, which is
going to be pretty damn soon,

536
00:30:13,440 --> 00:30:16,560
there are going to be huge chunks
of the moon heading right for us,

537
00:30:16,640 --> 00:30:19,800
like whatever killed the dinosaurs,
only 10,000 times bigger.

538
00:30:19,960 --> 00:30:22,640
But the moon isn't made of rock
and stone, is it? It's made of eggshell!

539
00:30:22,720 --> 00:30:25,480
Oh, God! Okay, okay, fine.

540
00:30:25,560 --> 00:30:28,240
If, by some miracle,
the shell isn't too thick

541
00:30:28,320 --> 00:30:31,640
or if it disperses or if it
goes into orbit, whatever,

542
00:30:31,720 --> 00:30:33,720
there's still going to be
a massive thing there, isn't there,

543
00:30:33,800 --> 00:30:35,960
that just popped out.

544
00:30:36,040 --> 00:30:38,320
And what the hell
do you imagine that is?

545
00:30:38,400 --> 00:30:39,680
Loads of things lay eggs.

546
00:30:41,160 --> 00:30:43,040
It's not a chicken.

547
00:30:43,120 --> 00:30:46,720
I'm not saying it's a chicken.
I'm not completely stupid.

548
00:30:47,760 --> 00:30:49,520
It's an exoparasite.

549
00:30:50,960 --> 00:30:52,800
-A what?
-Like a flea.

550
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:55,000
Or a head louse.

551
00:30:55,080 --> 00:30:56,440
I'm going to have to be
a lot more certain than that

552
00:30:56,520 --> 00:30:59,040
-if I'm going to kill a baby.
-Oh, you want to talk about babies?

553
00:30:59,120 --> 00:31:00,200
You've probably got babies
down there now.

554
00:31:00,280 --> 00:31:04,000
-You want to have babies?
-Well... Yeah.

555
00:31:04,400 --> 00:31:06,440
-Mr Pink...
-Shh!

556
00:31:06,520 --> 00:31:10,040
Okay, you imagine you've got children
down there on Earth now, right?

557
00:31:10,120 --> 00:31:11,680
Grandchildren, maybe.

558
00:31:11,760 --> 00:31:14,000
You want that thing to get out?
Kill them all?

559
00:31:15,080 --> 00:31:17,880
You want today to be the day
life on Earth stopped

560
00:31:17,960 --> 00:31:21,000
because you couldn't make
an unfair decision?

561
00:31:23,840 --> 00:31:26,080
Listen, I don't want to do this.

562
00:31:26,520 --> 00:31:29,400
All my life I've dreamed
about coming here.

563
00:31:30,960 --> 00:31:33,200
But this is how it has to end.

564
00:31:35,080 --> 00:31:36,080
Oi!

565
00:31:36,320 --> 00:31:39,240
I've given us an hour.
There's a cut-out here.

566
00:31:39,320 --> 00:31:41,640
If anyone has any bright ideas
or if he comes back, that stops it.

567
00:31:41,720 --> 00:31:45,040
But once it's pressed, it stays pressed.

568
00:31:46,080 --> 00:31:48,240
And if he doesn't come back?

569
00:31:49,480 --> 00:31:50,920
I didn't expect to survive anyway.

570
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:55,480
He's going to come back,
though, right? Isn't he, miss?

571
00:31:56,720 --> 00:31:58,640
Hey, why don't you call me Clara?

572
00:31:59,760 --> 00:32:01,320
I prefer "miss”, miss.

573
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:06,000
We just need to make up
our minds, that's all.

574
00:32:08,240 --> 00:32:10,200
Well, you know him.

575
00:32:11,800 --> 00:32:14,280
I think he really might just be
leaving it to us.

576
00:32:14,360 --> 00:32:15,920
(RADIO HISSING)

577
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:18,600
MAN: Can anybody hear me?
Come in, please.

578
00:32:18,680 --> 00:32:21,080
-Can anybody...
-Lundvik.

579
00:32:21,160 --> 00:32:24,640
-This is ground control.
-Yeah, yeah. I can tell by your haircut.

580
00:32:24,720 --> 00:32:28,000
-How are things down there?
- Pretty bad.

581
00:32:30,400 --> 00:32:32,640
Yeah. Pretty bad.

582
00:32:32,720 --> 00:32:34,480
Listen, we're patched in
to one of the TV satellites.

583
00:32:34,560 --> 00:32:36,880
We haven't got long.
How are things up there?

584
00:32:36,960 --> 00:32:39,000
-Can we broadcast on this?
-Who are you?

585
00:32:39,080 --> 00:32:42,560
School trip. Can we broadcast on this?

586
00:32:43,160 --> 00:32:44,280
Well, yes.

587
00:32:45,160 --> 00:32:46,600
Hello, Earth.

588
00:32:47,400 --> 00:32:49,320
We have a terrible decision to make.

589
00:32:50,240 --> 00:32:53,920
It's an uncertain decision
and we don't have a lot of time.

590
00:32:54,480 --> 00:32:56,720
We can kill this creature
or we can let it live.

591
00:32:56,800 --> 00:32:57,880
We don't know what it's going to do,

592
00:32:57,960 --> 00:32:59,520
we don't know what's going to happen
when it hatches,

593
00:32:59,600 --> 00:33:02,960
if it will hurt us, help us
or just leave us alone.

594
00:33:04,560 --> 00:33:07,080
We have to decide together.

595
00:33:07,160 --> 00:33:09,000
This is the last time
we'll be able to speak to you

596
00:33:09,080 --> 00:33:11,280
but you can send us a message.

597
00:33:13,560 --> 00:33:17,480
If you think we should
kill the creature, turn your lights off.

598
00:33:20,840 --> 00:33:23,920
If you think we should take the chance,

599
00:33:25,280 --> 00:33:29,320
let it live, leave your lights on.

600
00:33:30,160 --> 00:33:31,960
We'll be able to see.

601
00:33:33,880 --> 00:33:35,560
Goodnight, Earth.

602
00:33:43,960 --> 00:33:44,960
Was that okay?

603
00:33:46,880 --> 00:33:47,880
Yeah.

604
00:33:48,240 --> 00:33:49,960
(RUMBLING)

605
00:33:52,160 --> 00:33:54,040
Come on. Let's see.

606
00:34:32,160 --> 00:34:34,600
(BEEPING)

607
00:35:01,920 --> 00:35:03,360
Night-night.

608
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:07,320
Oh, Doctor, where have you gone?

609
00:35:09,360 --> 00:35:11,320
We can't risk it all just to be nice.

610
00:35:15,920 --> 00:35:17,640
-Okay.
-Miss.

611
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:21,320
-Nine seconds.
-You can't!

612
00:35:21,400 --> 00:35:24,200
Sorry, girls. See you on the other side.

613
00:35:25,880 --> 00:35:27,040
Two...

614
00:35:28,040 --> 00:35:29,120
Hey!

615
00:35:31,840 --> 00:35:33,760
-One, two, three, into the Tardis.
-What's happening?

616
00:35:33,840 --> 00:35:35,560
Let's go and have a look, shall we?

617
00:35:38,480 --> 00:35:41,760
Bloody idiots!
Bloody irresponsible idiots!

618
00:35:43,960 --> 00:35:46,000
Would you mind your language, please?
There are children present.

619
00:35:46,080 --> 00:35:47,760
You should
have left me there, let me die.

620
00:35:47,840 --> 00:35:49,520
I wanted to die up there with
the universe in front of me,

621
00:35:49,600 --> 00:35:51,120
not being crushed to death on Earth!

622
00:35:51,200 --> 00:35:52,680
Nobody's going to die!

623
00:35:52,760 --> 00:35:54,280
Could you please let us see
what's happening?

624
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:56,840
(WHOOSHING)

625
00:36:10,920 --> 00:36:13,880
-(LOUD GROAN IN DISTANCE)
-What's it doing?

626
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:16,520
It's feeling the sun on itself.

627
00:36:16,600 --> 00:36:17,920
It's getting warm.

628
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:22,200
The chick flies away
and the eggshell disintegrates.

629
00:36:22,720 --> 00:36:23,720
Harmless.

630
00:36:25,600 --> 00:36:26,600
Did you know?

631
00:36:29,200 --> 00:36:32,560
You made your decision.
Humanity made its choice.

632
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:34,600
No, we ignored humanity.

633
00:36:35,320 --> 00:36:37,040
Well, there you go.

634
00:36:38,080 --> 00:36:39,320
So what happens now, then?

635
00:36:39,840 --> 00:36:41,440
Tell me what happens now.

636
00:37:02,840 --> 00:37:04,760
In the mid-21st century,

637
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:10,000
humankind starts creeping off

638
00:37:10,080 --> 00:37:11,600
into the stars.

639
00:37:13,200 --> 00:37:17,360
Spreads its way through the galaxy,

640
00:37:19,720 --> 00:37:22,160
to the very edges of the universe.

641
00:37:23,000 --> 00:37:24,280
And it

642
00:37:26,280 --> 00:37:29,760
endures till the end of time.

643
00:37:37,160 --> 00:37:39,920
And it does all that
because one day in the year 2049,

644
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:43,360
when it had stopped thinking
about going to the stars,

645
00:37:43,440 --> 00:37:46,360
something occurred
that made it look up, not down.

646
00:37:46,440 --> 00:37:48,760
It looked out there into the blackness

647
00:37:48,840 --> 00:37:53,760
and it saw something beautiful,
something wonderful,

648
00:37:53,840 --> 00:37:56,200
that for once it didn't want to destroy.

649
00:37:56,280 --> 00:37:59,120
And in that one moment,

650
00:37:59,200 --> 00:38:01,920
the whole course of history was changed.

651
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:05,320
Not bad for a girl
from Coal Hill School.

652
00:38:06,080 --> 00:38:07,080
And her teacher.

653
00:38:09,600 --> 00:38:10,600
Oh, my gosh.

654
00:38:12,480 --> 00:38:14,040
It laid a new egg.

655
00:38:14,600 --> 00:38:16,120
It's beautiful.

656
00:38:16,960 --> 00:38:18,880
Doctor, it's beautiful.

657
00:38:19,800 --> 00:38:22,640
That's what we call a new moon.

658
00:38:23,880 --> 00:38:26,360
You can be the first woman on that!

659
00:38:28,240 --> 00:38:30,280
I think that somebody
deserves a thank you.

660
00:38:31,840 --> 00:38:33,360
Yeah, probably.

661
00:38:38,560 --> 00:38:39,560
Thank you.

662
00:38:41,280 --> 00:38:42,920
Thank you for stopping me.

663
00:38:43,760 --> 00:38:46,400
Thank you for giving me the moon back.

664
00:38:48,040 --> 00:38:50,600
Okay, Captain. Well, you've
got a whole new space programme

665
00:38:50,680 --> 00:38:53,840
to get together. NASA is, uh...

666
00:38:53,920 --> 00:38:56,120
that way. About 2,500 miles.

667
00:38:56,200 --> 00:38:58,920
You still got your Vortex Manipulators?
I'll give you a run home.

668
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:15,360
Not that it's any of my business
but I think you did the right thing.

669
00:39:15,440 --> 00:39:17,120
Yeah, you're right.
It's none of your business.

670
00:39:17,200 --> 00:39:19,360
Come on, Courtney, off you go.
Double geography.

671
00:39:19,440 --> 00:39:22,400
-Can we do it again?
-Go! Go, go. Chop-chop.

672
00:39:24,200 --> 00:39:26,000
(WHOOSHING)

673
00:39:28,320 --> 00:39:30,320
(WHOOSHING STOPS)

674
00:39:31,800 --> 00:39:34,120
Tell me what you knew.

675
00:39:36,520 --> 00:39:39,280
Nothing.
I told you, I've got grey areas.

676
00:39:39,360 --> 00:39:41,840
Yeah, I noticed.
Tell me what you knew, Doctor,

677
00:39:41,920 --> 00:39:44,680
or else I'll smack you so hard
you'll regenerate.

678
00:39:48,400 --> 00:39:50,160
I knew that eggs are not bombs.

679
00:39:50,240 --> 00:39:52,360
I know they don't usually
destroy their nests.

680
00:39:52,440 --> 00:39:57,040
Essentially, what I knew was that
you would always make the best choice.

681
00:39:57,120 --> 00:39:59,840
I had faith that you would
always make the right choice.

682
00:40:01,560 --> 00:40:02,920
Honestly, do you have
music playing in your head

683
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:04,000
when you say rubbish like that?

684
00:40:04,080 --> 00:40:06,120
It wasn't my decision to make.
I told you.

685
00:40:06,200 --> 00:40:08,800
Well, why did you do it?
Was it for Courtney, was that it?

686
00:40:08,880 --> 00:40:11,840
Well, she really is
something special now, isn't she?

687
00:40:11,920 --> 00:40:14,360
First woman on the moon,
saved the Earth from itself

688
00:40:14,440 --> 00:40:17,480
and rather bizarrely, she becomes
the President of the United States!

689
00:40:17,560 --> 00:40:18,760
She met this bloke called Blinovitch...

690
00:40:18,840 --> 00:40:22,640
Do you know what? Shut up!
I am so sick of listening to you!

691
00:40:28,160 --> 00:40:30,360
Well, I didn't do it for Courtney.

692
00:40:30,440 --> 00:40:32,680
I didn't know what was going to happen.

693
00:40:33,040 --> 00:40:35,560
-What, do you think I'm lying?
-I don't know. I don't know!

694
00:40:35,640 --> 00:40:38,280
If you didn't do it for her, I mean...

695
00:40:38,360 --> 00:40:41,920
Do you know what, it was...
It was cheap, it was pathetic.

696
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:43,480
No, no, no. It was patronising.

697
00:40:43,560 --> 00:40:45,240
That was you patting us
on the back, saying,

698
00:40:45,320 --> 00:40:47,040
"You're big enough to go
to the shops by yourself now.

699
00:40:47,120 --> 00:40:48,200
"Go on, toddle along."

700
00:40:48,280 --> 00:40:51,880
No, that was me allowing you to
make a choice about your own future.

701
00:40:51,960 --> 00:40:54,680
That was me respecting you.

702
00:40:55,160 --> 00:40:56,440
Oh, my God, really? Was it?

703
00:40:56,520 --> 00:40:59,360
Yeah, well, respected is not how I feel.

704
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:05,200
Right. Okay. Uh...

705
00:41:05,280 --> 00:41:07,240
I nearly didn't press that button.

706
00:41:07,320 --> 00:41:12,240
I nearly got it wrong. That was you,
my friend, making me scared,

707
00:41:12,320 --> 00:41:14,440
-making me feel like a bloody idiot...
-Language!

708
00:41:14,520 --> 00:41:16,240
Oh, don't you ever tell me
to mind my language,

709
00:41:16,320 --> 00:41:19,640
don't you ever tell me to
take the stabilisers off my bike

710
00:41:19,720 --> 00:41:22,320
and don't you dare lump me in
with the rest of all the little humans

711
00:41:22,400 --> 00:41:26,200
that you think are so tiny
and silly and predictable!

712
00:41:27,880 --> 00:41:31,240
You walk our Earth, Doctor,
you breathe our air,

713
00:41:31,320 --> 00:41:33,000
you make us your friend,
then that is your moon, too,

714
00:41:33,080 --> 00:41:35,280
and you can damn well help us
when we need it!

715
00:41:35,360 --> 00:41:36,960
-I was helping.
-What, by clearing off?

716
00:41:37,040 --> 00:41:38,520
-Yes!
-Yeah, well, clear off!

717
00:41:39,360 --> 00:41:40,800
Go on.

718
00:41:40,880 --> 00:41:44,560
You can clear off. Get back in
your lonely, your lonely bloody Tardis

719
00:41:44,640 --> 00:41:46,040
and you don't come back!

720
00:41:48,720 --> 00:41:49,920
Clara. Clara!

721
00:41:52,800 --> 00:41:54,200
You go away.

722
00:41:55,320 --> 00:41:56,440
Okay?

723
00:41:58,360 --> 00:42:00,280
You go a long way away.

724
00:42:04,440 --> 00:42:06,000
(DOOR SLAMS)

725
00:42:13,080 --> 00:42:14,840
(WHOOSHING)

726
00:42:31,760 --> 00:42:34,080
-Hello.
-Hey! Now, then.

727
00:42:34,160 --> 00:42:36,640
-What've you been up to?
-The usual.

728
00:42:41,960 --> 00:42:43,320
It happened, didn't it?

729
00:42:46,080 --> 00:42:48,320
Well, he was wrong, wasn't he?

730
00:42:48,960 --> 00:42:49,960
Wasn't he?

731
00:42:50,640 --> 00:42:52,440
Danny, what do you think?

732
00:42:52,520 --> 00:42:53,760
I think I've seen this look before.

733
00:42:53,840 --> 00:42:55,480
No, you haven't. This is new for me.

734
00:42:55,800 --> 00:42:57,560
No, not on your face, on mine.

735
00:42:57,640 --> 00:42:59,680
-What did you do?
-I left the army.

736
00:42:59,760 --> 00:43:01,040
You loved the army.

737
00:43:01,120 --> 00:43:02,960
Yep. And then one day I didn't.

738
00:43:03,040 --> 00:43:07,880
I'm done, I'm done.
I am finished with it. I am... I'm done.

739
00:43:07,960 --> 00:43:11,400
It's over. I'm finished with him
and I told him that.

740
00:43:12,520 --> 00:43:14,400
What is that face for?
Why don't you believe me?

741
00:43:14,480 --> 00:43:16,200
Because you're still angry.

742
00:43:16,280 --> 00:43:19,560
You're never finished with anyone
while they can still make you angry.

743
00:43:20,240 --> 00:43:22,480
Tell him when you're calm, then tell me.

744
00:43:31,560 --> 00:43:33,680
When did you get to become so wise?

745
00:43:33,760 --> 00:43:35,800
Same way as anyone else.

746
00:43:36,720 --> 00:43:38,320
I had a really bad day.

747
00:44:09,040 --> 00:44:12,440
DOCTOR: There were many trains
to take the name Orient Express

748
00:44:12,520 --> 00:44:15,240
but only one in space.

749
00:44:15,320 --> 00:44:16,440
MAN: Good morning, everyone.

750
00:44:16,520 --> 00:44:19,520
Your goal is to ascertain
the Foretold's true nature.

751
00:44:19,960 --> 00:44:21,560
I know exactly what this sounds like.

752
00:44:21,640 --> 00:44:22,960
MAN: Isn't this exciting?

753
00:44:23,040 --> 00:44:24,960
